    <body>

        <div xml:id="AN121.2-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">C2+3+7+9v: tōḻiyāṟ [ṟalaimakaḷai yuṭa]ṉvarumeṉak kēṭṭa talaimakaṉ ṟaṉṉeñciṟkuc collic 
            celavaḻuṅkiyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">How HE, who had heard that it was said by the confidante to HER 
            that she would come along, prevented going by speaking to his heart.</p>
        </div>
        <div xml:id="AN121.2">
            <lg type="edition">
                <l><supplied>nānakai yuṭaiya neñcē</supplied> kaṭuntiṟal</l>
                <l>vēṉi ṉīṭiya vāṉuyar vaḻināḷ </l>
                <l>vaṟumai kūṟiya maṇṇīrc ciṟukkuḷat</l>
                <l>toṭukuḻi maruṅkiṟ ṟūvaṟ kalaṅkal</l>
                <l>kaṉṟuṭai maṭap<supplied>piṭi kayantalai maṇṇi</supplied>c</l>
                <l>cēṟukoṇ ṭāṭiya vēṟupaṭu vayakkaḷiṟu</l>
                <l>ceṅkōl vāliṇar tayaṅkat tīṇṭic</l>
                <l>coṟipuṟa muriñciya neṟiyayaṉ marā<supplied>at</supplied></l>
                <l><supplied>talkuṟu variniḻa la</supplied>caii nammoṭu</l>
                <l>tāṉvaru meṉpa taṭameṉ ṟōḷi</l>
                <l>yuṟukaṇ maḻava ruḷkīṇ ṭiṭṭa</l>
                <l>vāṟuceṉ mākkaḷ cōṟupoti veṇ<supplied>kuṭaik</supplied></l>
                <l><supplied>kaṉmi</supplied>caik kaṭuvaḷi yeṭuttaliṟ ṟuṇaicettu</l>
                <l>veruḷēṟu payiru māṅkaṭ</l>
                <l>karumuka mucuviṉ kā<supplied>ṉa</supplied>t tāṉē</l>
            </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <l>We are smiling, heart: on the last day</l>
                <l>high in the sky when fierce, powerful summer [heat] has lasted long, (1-2)</l>
                <l>she with broad soft shoulders, they say, will come in person (10)</l>
                <l>with us, resting in the dwindling dappled shade</l> 
                <l>of the Kadamba tree near the path on which the transformed strong elephant bull</l>
                <l>rubs [its] itching back, bumping the red-stemmed white clusters</l>
                <l>so that they swayed, [the bull] who had bathed, taking mud,</l>
                <l>washing the soft head of [its] youthful cow that has a calf</l>
                <l>with the spattering muddy water from a pit he dug</l>
                <l>in the pond little in water, with earth [showing] that speaks of scarcity (3-9)</l>
                <l>– in the forest of the black-faced langur,</l>
                <l>that place where the startled bull calls,</l>
                <l>thinking of [its] mate because the fierce wind lifts, on the stones,</l>
                <l>the white baskets with the stores of rice  of the people going on the road</l>
                <l>which is cleaved by the [chariot] wheels of suffering warriors. (11-15)</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
